<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-652-168  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 652 168.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  July 2 1990 v219 n1 p8(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Argentina becomes Bell Atlantic's latest port of call. (Bell winscontract to manage telephone company) (News of the Week)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Luxner, Larry.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Bell Atlantic has won a contract to provide the management for oneof the two new Argentine telephone companies formed from thebreakup of its state-owned company, Empresa Nacional deTelecomunicaciones (Entel).andP;  The successful bid was: $100 millionin cash, $1.86 in debt paper, and $372 million in outstandinginterest on the debt.andP;  Bell's part of Entel will providetelecommunications services to the Northern half of the country.andO;Argentina's telephone system is one of the worst in Latin America:the equipment was mainly installed in the 1930s and citizens mustwait up to 15 years to get a phone line.andP;  This is Bell Atlantic'sthird major overseas venture, following contracts with New ZealandTelecom and the Czechoslovakian public network.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Bell Atlantic Corp. (foreign operations)Empresa Nacional de Telecomunicaciones (Argentina) (management).andO;Ticker:    BEL.andO;Topic:     ContractsTelephone companiesArgentinaBell Regional Holding CompaniesInternational.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>